1
00:00:12,832 --> 00:00:16,791
Everyone is alone
and no one cares about anyone

2
00:00:16,952 --> 00:00:19,952
And our pains
are a deserted island...

3
00:00:20,151 --> 00:00:23,391
To Jacques Brel.

4
00:00:51,710 --> 00:00:57,630
who will give a circus
show for me

5
00:00:57,790 --> 00:01:04,830
nostalgic love in the dust

6
00:01:04,990 --> 00:01:09,629
who will make me go "I'm scared"

7
00:01:09,749 --> 00:01:15,949
the knife in the heart,
in the limelight

8
00:01:16,949 --> 00:01:21,629
who will treat me like a tigress

9
00:01:21,828 --> 00:01:28,588
the whip like
a caress to the music

10
00:01:28,749 --> 00:01:32,028
who will make me

11
00:01:32,188 --> 00:01:38,188
balance between
balloons full of pathos

12
00:01:38,308 --> 00:01:42,827
sometimes I panic

13
00:01:43,948 --> 00:01:48,908
who will tell me

14
00:01:49,067 --> 00:01:56,027
words of love
that can hurt

15
00:01:56,187 --> 00:01:57,707
who will hold me

16
00:01:58,187 --> 00:02:01,947
ITINERARY OF A SPOILED CHILD

17
00:02:02,467 --> 00:02:08,107
when you'll release
all the stars

18
00:02:08,266 --> 00:02:13,066
who will want me

19
00:02:13,226 --> 00:02:19,946
with my red nose and
my heart full of tears

20
00:02:20,106 --> 00:02:25,026
who will love me

21
00:02:25,226 --> 00:02:31,785
when there won't be much
of me left anymore

22
00:02:35,065 --> 00:02:40,185
who will still make me dream

23
00:02:40,345 --> 00:02:47,065
the clown or the rider
who emerges from the shadow

24
00:02:47,225 --> 00:02:52,265
who will still bring me the
artist's performance

25
00:02:52,385 --> 00:02:59,784
the trapeze artist's show
see him fall

26
00:02:59,944 --> 00:03:05,064
who will still bring me
the child that plays

27
00:03:05,224 --> 00:03:11,863
for the performing dogs
or the vampires

28
00:03:12,504 --> 00:03:14,263
Don't you have a ticket?

29
00:03:15,383 --> 00:03:17,944
Where's your mother?

30
00:03:19,384 --> 00:03:22,023
Where? In the bar?

31
00:03:23,063 --> 00:03:28,343
Wait, I'll check. This boy
says his mother's in the bar.

32
00:03:28,503 --> 00:03:33,303
Could you have a look?
Ask for the mother of the boy.

33
00:03:33,462 --> 00:03:38,742
Wait a moment.
What's your name?

34
00:03:40,942 --> 00:03:42,902
Sam?

35
00:03:43,062 --> 00:03:49,062
What have you got there?
Can I have a look?

36
00:03:49,222 --> 00:03:50,981
Is that your mother's?

37
00:04:02,981 --> 00:04:07,621
Sam's three years old. I can't
keep him. I'm desperate.

38
00:04:07,781 --> 00:04:11,381
Look after him. I beg you.

39
00:04:11,501 --> 00:04:14,421
three years later

40
00:05:13,658 --> 00:05:16,338
Sam, 13 years old

41
00:06:21,375 --> 00:06:23,455
Sam, 16 years old

42
00:08:17,930 --> 00:08:24,409
it has a silver shine

43
00:08:24,529 --> 00:08:31,288
the itinerary of a spoiled child

44
00:08:31,408 --> 00:08:36,489
is littered with broken toys

45
00:08:37,928 --> 00:08:44,408
the itinerary of a spoiled child

46
00:08:45,928 --> 00:08:49,928
The last time I saw him,
was just before he left.

47
00:08:50,048 --> 00:08:53,048
He wanted to get to know
himself.

48
00:08:53,208 --> 00:08:59,287
This solitary voyage was a challenge
he added to all the storms in his 
life.

49
00:08:59,448 --> 00:09:04,968
He always said: when I spend some
hours with you, I want to believe.

50
00:09:05,127 --> 00:09:10,687
When I spend an evening with my
children, I want to believe in family.

51
00:09:11,767 --> 00:09:15,527
When I'm with a woman,
I want to believe in love.

52
00:09:15,647 --> 00:09:17,966
That's Sam Lion for you.

53
00:09:18,086 --> 00:09:20,567
You know why he was called that,
don't you?

54
00:09:20,687 --> 00:09:27,287
He was found near a circus and
when he was registered...

55
00:09:27,446 --> 00:09:34,406
the circus master called him Sam Lion
because he was always near the lions.

56
00:09:35,406 --> 00:09:40,326
This is the best day of my life.
-Because it's beautiful here.

57
00:09:40,446 --> 00:09:43,205
Where does all this water go?
-To Lake Kariba.

58
00:09:43,325 --> 00:09:49,285
It's beautiful. Rainbows
come straight out of the water.

59
00:09:49,445 --> 00:09:51,365
The most beautiful spot
in the world.

60
00:09:51,525 --> 00:09:53,765
Will we see all of that?

61
00:09:53,925 --> 00:09:55,685
You and I?

62
00:09:58,805 --> 00:10:01,925
Look a rainbow. Quick.
Make a wish.

63
00:10:02,045 --> 00:10:05,004
When he falls from the trapeze,
he becomes a street sweeper...

64
00:10:05,484 --> 00:10:07,245
so he can stay with the carnival.

65
00:10:07,845 --> 00:10:13,524
He wins a prize for best sweeper
and gets the award from Yvette...

66
00:10:13,684 --> 00:10:17,524
who becomes his wife.
They have a son, Jean-Philippe.

67
00:10:17,644 --> 00:10:21,524
Then the big drama happens
in Singapore.

68
00:10:21,644 --> 00:10:25,443
He has to raise Jean-Philippe
on his own.

69
00:10:25,604 --> 00:10:30,644
It takes him ten years to
recover and meet Corine.

70
00:10:30,803 --> 00:10:34,083
Ten years to turn his little
business into an international 
company.

71
00:10:34,283 --> 00:10:38,563
Ten years before he can smile again
upon seeing a child's face.

72
00:10:38,683 --> 00:10:40,483
Magnificent.

73
00:10:43,042 --> 00:10:48,482
You look more and more like your 
mother.
-Then you must be starting to hate me.

74
00:10:49,642 --> 00:10:53,762
Whose idea was it to go here?
-Mine.

75
00:10:53,922 --> 00:10:58,322
I wanted to go to Venice,
but Corine had already been there.

76
00:10:58,442 --> 00:11:01,521
Then I realised they have even more
water here.

77
00:11:01,682 --> 00:11:05,282
Who decided to call me Victoria?
-Your mother.

78
00:11:05,442 --> 00:11:10,561
She's sure you were conceived here.
In this area.

79
00:11:10,681 --> 00:11:13,761
I'm glad it wasn't near the
Niagara Falls.

80
00:11:13,921 --> 00:11:19,761
You were almost called Isabelle.
Because I loved Jacques Brels song.

81
00:11:19,921 --> 00:11:22,561
It's about his daughter.

82
00:11:22,721 --> 00:11:26,881
But because of this spectacle,
you became Victoria.

83
00:11:27,041 --> 00:11:29,600
How did you get the business?

84
00:11:29,761 --> 00:11:36,320
After my accident, I was responsible
for keeping the circus clean.

85
00:11:36,440 --> 00:11:40,080
I looked for machines to do the work.

86
00:11:43,800 --> 00:11:46,000
What shall we do tonight?

87
00:11:46,159 --> 00:11:52,079
American dinner, tamtam, birthday 
cake,
champagne. The good life.

88
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:56,879
Doesn't that give you ideas?
-Why not?

89
00:11:57,040 --> 00:12:02,719
I watched them this morning.
It's great what they do.

90
00:12:02,879 --> 00:12:09,438
Look, he's the best one.
Unbelievable what he does.

91
00:12:11,039 --> 00:12:17,199
Imagine, autumn on the Champs-Elysées.
'Ballet with Brooms'.

92
00:12:45,837 --> 00:12:50,077
When will the machines be introduced?
-In a month.

93
00:12:50,236 --> 00:12:51,597
How did you get the idea?

94
00:12:51,757 --> 00:12:58,156
My daughter and I saw them on our
travels and we improved on them.

95
00:12:58,316 --> 00:13:01,996
They say a minister is interested
in buying them.

96
00:13:02,156 --> 00:13:06,156
That makes sense.
It's of interest to the public.

97
00:13:06,316 --> 00:13:10,716
Are you really going to buy
a circus that has gone bankrupt?

98
00:13:10,875 --> 00:13:13,916
I love the circus,
but that's nonsense.

99
00:13:14,036 --> 00:13:20,556
I only hired people who were about to 
be
fired. This is my secretary, by the 
way.

100
00:13:20,715 --> 00:13:27,515
The only secretary to land safely 
after
a death-defying leap. Most of the 
time.

101
00:13:27,635 --> 00:13:32,315
How did you become the biggest
in your trade, in 10 years?

102
00:13:32,435 --> 00:13:36,875
Step in the shit often
and always clean it up.

103
00:13:38,155 --> 00:13:42,395
So this machine will
replace street sweepers?

104
00:13:42,515 --> 00:13:47,194
This machine can clean 10
kilometres per day.

105
00:13:47,314 --> 00:13:49,594
A person can do 1 kilometre.

106
00:13:49,754 --> 00:13:55,434
The operator can also use the
machine as a mode of transport.

107
00:13:55,554 --> 00:14:01,433
But most of all, the operator doesn't
make contact with the garbage anymore.

108
00:14:01,553 --> 00:14:07,913
The work will get a better reputation
and will also be performed by 
students.

109
00:14:08,033 --> 00:14:10,553
So, sweepers will be unemployed.

110
00:14:10,673 --> 00:14:17,513
The machine can't reach everywhere and
traditional sweepers are still 
required.

111
00:14:17,673 --> 00:14:21,113
But they should learn to
use roller-skates.

112
00:14:30,392 --> 00:14:33,592
Do you find this funny?
-Not at all.

113
00:14:33,752 --> 00:14:36,392
I need to talk to you.
-I understand.

114
00:14:36,512 --> 00:14:41,752
What do you mean?
-I'm just saying I understand.

115
00:14:41,912 --> 00:14:44,792
I don't want to go to the hotel.

116
00:14:44,912 --> 00:14:47,591
It's not a hotel,
it's where I live.

117
00:14:47,751 --> 00:14:50,711
It's also about the rest.

118
00:14:50,871 --> 00:14:55,911
What? I don't have anything.
This machine's my first moped.

119
00:14:56,031 --> 00:14:58,231
What do you want?

120
00:14:59,911 --> 00:15:05,510
What do I have to do to keep you?
Drive a pink Cadillac?

121
00:15:08,311 --> 00:15:11,911
Wait a moment. Wait.

122
00:15:12,070 --> 00:15:15,030
Here, this is for you.

123
00:15:15,150 --> 00:15:18,230
What is it?
-Have a look.

124
00:15:19,510 --> 00:15:24,870
I'd like to take you there.
Near Victoria Falls.

125
00:15:34,629 --> 00:15:39,029
Are you going? Alright.

126
00:15:39,189 --> 00:15:43,189
Can I keep this?
-It's a present.

127
00:16:23,907 --> 00:16:27,906
Will you be roller-skating for long?
-I don't know.

128
00:16:28,026 --> 00:16:33,507
Aren't you taking that thing?
-Leave it. I'll take it tomorrow.

129
00:16:36,906 --> 00:16:40,786
When will you get married?
-Ask him.

130
00:16:40,946 --> 00:16:46,466
Miss, bring me the file of
Albert Duvivier.

131
00:16:46,625 --> 00:16:51,106
It's a machine to pick up shit with,
not girls.

132
00:16:51,266 --> 00:16:54,785
And how often have I told you
to wear your helmet?

133
00:16:54,905 --> 00:16:59,105
Can I speak to the boss?
-I'm your direct superior.

134
00:16:59,265 --> 00:17:04,385
I want to speak to whoever makes the
rules, not to who enforces them.

135
00:17:04,505 --> 00:17:08,665
Can you swim?
-Breast stroke.

136
00:17:08,785 --> 00:17:13,785
Swim into the Atlantic
Ocean and you might see him.

137
00:17:23,864 --> 00:17:25,664
Damn.

138
00:17:55,103 --> 00:17:59,982
That's not clear. Repeat, please.
-Your position, Victoria?

139
00:18:00,102 --> 00:18:03,743
I repeat 42 North, 26 West.

140
00:18:06,102 --> 00:18:10,142
Still the same.
Speak clearly, dear.

141
00:18:10,262 --> 00:18:15,982
I ask him to call you.
-In an hour. I have things to do.

142
00:18:16,141 --> 00:18:18,702
End of call.
-Fine.

143
00:18:21,022 --> 00:18:26,221
So that's 42 North...
That's not my position at all.

144
00:18:27,501 --> 00:18:31,021
Hello, Saint-Lys.

145
00:18:36,461 --> 00:18:41,181
Is there anybody at the pump?
-Céline. I'm here.

146
00:18:41,340 --> 00:18:44,781
What do I have to do?
-Help them with the crossing.

147
00:18:44,940 --> 00:18:47,660
How long will that take?
-Two weeks.

148
00:18:47,820 --> 00:18:51,260
Will I be washing dishes
for two weeks?

149
00:19:00,779 --> 00:19:04,779
Victoria Lion
Starting Point

150
00:19:10,819 --> 00:19:15,579
I'll summarize.
Take it easy with the pills.

151
00:19:15,739 --> 00:19:18,939
What's more important...
Are you listening?

152
00:19:19,059 --> 00:19:25,018
Take your boat out mornings,
afternoons and evenings...

153
00:19:25,138 --> 00:19:30,139
and get far away from us,
for at least a month.

154
00:19:31,258 --> 00:19:34,658
You can't quit smoking like
that either.

155
00:19:36,058 --> 00:19:37,818
Want to bet?

156
00:19:41,298 --> 00:19:44,138
Is it that serious?
-It's in your head.

157
00:19:44,298 --> 00:19:47,577
That's good.
I'll see you at dinner.

158
00:19:47,737 --> 00:19:51,018
Are you still with Martine?
-I'll tell you later.

159
00:19:51,138 --> 00:19:55,977
Jean-Philippe,
your father's not doing well.

160
00:19:56,137 --> 00:19:59,257
I fear a nervous breakdown.

161
00:19:59,377 --> 00:20:02,936
He shouldn't continue to live
close to his work.

162
00:20:03,097 --> 00:20:07,577
It's not good to live in a caravan,
especially for him.

163
00:20:07,736 --> 00:20:13,337
I'll give him a prescription, but talk
to him. We have to get through to him.

164
00:20:14,376 --> 00:20:17,896
Is he doing that bad?

165
00:20:19,656 --> 00:20:24,535
What is happiness then?
-You'd like to know, wouldn't you?

166
00:20:24,696 --> 00:20:31,655
Well, happiness is... it's...

167
00:20:31,816 --> 00:20:36,775
When there is no trouble.
And you have to keep it that way.

168
00:20:36,935 --> 00:20:40,215
You must be very tired
to talk like that.

169
00:20:40,655 --> 00:20:43,655
What tired you out the most in life?

170
00:20:43,815 --> 00:20:45,335
Your mother.

171
00:20:46,335 --> 00:20:50,254
Didn't you love her a bit?
-Yes.

172
00:20:50,454 --> 00:20:52,774
Or you wouldn't have
been born.

173
00:20:52,935 --> 00:20:56,134
And did you love Jean-Philippe's
mother?

174
00:20:57,334 --> 00:21:03,014
Can't we talk about something else?
-You don't want to talk about anyone.

175
00:21:04,014 --> 00:21:05,894
Are you angry with me?

176
00:21:06,053 --> 00:21:11,174
I'm glad you still look human.
You should see the car.

177
00:21:11,333 --> 00:21:16,934
Can you explain to me why
we don't get along, dad?

178
00:21:17,973 --> 00:21:21,013
I've sent you to schools that were
too good.

179
00:21:23,173 --> 00:21:29,332
While we both run Victoria,
I can't be myself.

180
00:21:31,093 --> 00:21:34,652
Hold on a bit longer.
I won't stay for long.

181
00:21:34,772 --> 00:21:42,012
That's not what I mean. You sleep at
Victoria, you eat it, you drink it.

182
00:21:42,212 --> 00:21:45,772
You sail Victoria.
It's all you think about.

183
00:21:45,892 --> 00:21:50,052
We never have time to talk.
To spend an evening together.

184
00:21:56,772 --> 00:22:01,731
Do you really want to cross the ocean?
-I've been sailing for 30 years.

185
00:22:01,851 --> 00:22:04,691
The bay of St. Tropez isn't
the same thing.

186
00:22:04,851 --> 00:22:08,291
Anything urgent?
I'm not available for anyone.

187
00:22:08,451 --> 00:22:10,771
You can't do this.

188
00:22:10,931 --> 00:22:15,571
Can't I go out on the ocean?
-You're abandoning 12,000 employees.

189
00:22:15,731 --> 00:22:19,650
No, I'm not.
I'm selling a company. Quite a 
company.

190
00:22:19,811 --> 00:22:22,610
You can't. You are the company.

191
00:22:22,770 --> 00:22:26,530
Who can buy a company like that?
-What about these walls?

192
00:22:26,690 --> 00:22:31,489
What will you do with the money?
-I haven't had a break for 50 years.

193
00:22:31,650 --> 00:22:36,049
Two days of holiday and you'll go mad.
-I want to try.

194
00:22:54,609 --> 00:22:58,608
The doctor said he won't start again.
-What should I do?

195
00:22:58,769 --> 00:23:02,608
Look.
-What should I do?

196
00:23:02,769 --> 00:23:04,128
Ride a bicycle.

197
00:23:04,288 --> 00:23:09,168
Look at him. He goes from
one to the next. Look.

198
00:23:11,008 --> 00:23:16,288
I want to write a book. Think I can?
-A book? Why not?

199
00:23:16,448 --> 00:23:22,287
And I want to go to the US.
-Is he American?

200
00:23:24,848 --> 00:23:26,687
Unbelievable.

201
00:23:26,807 --> 00:23:31,487
You always take me to the circus.
-Of course.

202
00:23:32,807 --> 00:23:36,127
My two big passions in life.

203
00:23:37,407 --> 00:23:41,647
When I was young,
I always wanted to marry you.

204
00:23:41,767 --> 00:23:46,526
And now?
-I'd be too scared you'd leave me.

205
00:23:46,687 --> 00:23:49,726
But I do want someone like you.

206
00:23:49,846 --> 00:23:53,646
Shall I tell you something?
I'm not a good catch.

207
00:23:53,806 --> 00:23:56,126
I don't believe that.
-It's true.

208
00:23:56,246 --> 00:24:01,086
What's a good catch?
-Someone who doesn't think too much.

209
00:24:01,245 --> 00:24:05,005
That only leaves the idiots.
-Don't believe that.

210
00:24:09,846 --> 00:24:12,525
Better late than never.

211
00:24:12,685 --> 00:24:15,405
You're even late on the day
of your divorce.

212
00:24:15,565 --> 00:24:17,725
Especially then.

213
00:24:20,804 --> 00:24:25,644
Don't they know what the party's for?
-I was waiting for you.

214
00:24:25,764 --> 00:24:31,004
Is this a joke?
-Don't pull that face. It's a party.

215
00:24:31,164 --> 00:24:36,444
You should celebrate the day of 
escape,
not the day of imprisonment.

216
00:24:36,604 --> 00:24:40,044
Isn't she beautiful,
my divorced wife?

217
00:24:45,564 --> 00:24:47,884
You look good.
-So do you.

218
00:24:48,043 --> 00:24:51,883
Will she be in time?
-I think so.

219
00:24:52,043 --> 00:24:55,403
When did she decide to come back?
-The day before yesterday.

220
00:24:55,563 --> 00:25:01,003
I knew she wouldn't like New-York.
She's too French.

221
00:25:01,163 --> 00:25:05,483
What's wrong?
-Nothing. Everything's fine.

222
00:25:05,643 --> 00:25:07,403
Look, there she is.

223
00:25:09,882 --> 00:25:14,362
What has she got in her arms?
-She'll explain later.

224
00:25:15,402 --> 00:25:21,482
You explain it to me.
-He's six months old and his name's 
Sam.

225
00:25:29,482 --> 00:25:35,241
His name's Sam, he's six months old
and I'm the grandfather. Is that 
right?

226
00:25:38,681 --> 00:25:41,001
Where's the father?

227
00:25:42,441 --> 00:25:45,481
Not here. Of course.

228
00:25:47,481 --> 00:25:50,200
Does the father know, at least?

229
00:25:51,560 --> 00:25:53,560
It's better like this.

230
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:58,040
Do you want to know what
I really think?

231
00:26:02,440 --> 00:26:08,120
I'm the happiest man in the world.
Look, he's got my eyes.

232
00:26:08,280 --> 00:26:12,200
Not because she's my daughter,
but it's great.

233
00:26:12,360 --> 00:26:15,319
I would love it if you could
publish it.

234
00:26:15,480 --> 00:26:19,239
If there's a problem,
you know where to find me.

235
00:26:19,399 --> 00:26:22,119
Don't tell my daughter, please.

